What I am trying to convey through this article is that, if you are trying to build performance efficient application and if you want to choose between node and go, then go with go.
Here is the link to a small experiment that I did with node and go to know which one is better in terms of performance - 
https://github.com/PraGitHub/Prapository/tree/master/Misc/Node%20vs%20Go

Following are my findings,

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Node
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    N = 206134
    Time taken for QuickSort:
        436 milliseconds
        474 milliseconds
        483 milliseconds
        463 milliseconds
    Avg: 
        464 milliseconds

    Time taken for BubbleSort:
        5 min 30 seconds
        5 min 32 seconds
        5 min 13 seconds
        5 min 22 seconds
    Avg:
        5 min 24 seconds

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Go
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    N = 206134
    Time taken for QuickSort:
        46 milliseconds
        29 milliseconds
        33 milliseconds
        32 milliseconds
    Avg:
        35 milliseconds


    Time taken for BubbleSort:
        32 seconds
        33 seconds
        33 seconds
        33 seconds
    Avg:
        33 seconds

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Conclision
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

node took an average of 464 milliseconds to sort 206134 elements using quick sort
go only took an average of 35 milliseconds to do the same

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

node took an average of 5 min 24 seconds to sort 206134 elements using bubble sort
go only took an average of 33 seconds to do the same

